article.headline: Wyoming 63, Montana State 55
article.story: CASPER, Wyo. (AP) -- A veteran and a freshman came to Wyoming's rescue on Saturday. Senior David Adams keyed a fourth-quarter run and newcomer Mikel Watson hit a crucial 3-pointer as Wyoming escaped with a 63-55 victory over Montana State in the Blue Cross/Blue Shield Wyoming Shootout at the Casper Events Center. "I told (Adams) last night in practice 'You're getting good shots, you just have to step up and knock them down," Cowboys coach Steve McClain said. Wyoming (4-3), which trailed 30-29 at halftime, moved ahead 58-54 with 3:05 remaining on the last of Adams' four 3-pointers. The senior shooting guard finished with a game-high 20 points. Montana State's tight zone defense slowed down the Cowboys' up-tempo style and held Wyoming 11 points below its average. "We wanted to mix up our defenses because we knew that they were going to need help in the post," Montana State coach Mick Durham said. "Since we did that, I think they (UW) were a little hesitant to shoot the ball in the first half." With 1:10 remaining and three seconds on the shot clock, Watson hit a 3-pointer from the right wing to put Wyoming ahead, 61-55. Montana State missed three of four free throws in the final 2:40 and went 1-for-6 from the line in the game. "That last shot by Watson was a backbreaker for us," Durham said. "We played good defense the whole possession, and he hit a big shot." Calvin Ento led Montana State (3-4) with 19 points, while Jason Erickson had 12. Starting center Matt Townsley did not play in the contest and is expected to miss two-to-three weeks with a herniated disc in his back. Joe Ries scored 13 points for Wyoming, which was without starting guard Dion Sherrell, who sprained his foot in Friday's shootaround. His status was uncertain. Wyoming has beaten Montana State nine consecutive times. The Bobcats last win in the series was on Dec. 16, 1962. "They haven't beaten us, but they make us better," McClain said.
